7. Pax Samnitium, ‘ the peace with the Samnites.' Cicero is misled here by patriotic prejudice. The conduct of the Romans, so far from being an instance of ‘ honestas' prevailing over ‘ species utilitatis,’ is rather a proof that ‘the Romans were as regardless of their own individual feelingS‚ as of the laws of justice and good faith, when either were set in the balance against national pride and ambition.’ Arnold, Hist. of Rome, vol. 2, ch. 31.
